    "post_id": 66622,
    "title": "Schedule for the Reading of Psalms and Hafṭarot corresponding to the Weekly Torah Portion (and Hafṭarot for Festivals) according to the Damascus Ḳaraites (ca. 1700)",
    "author": "Isaac Gantwerk Mayer (translation)",
    "coauthors": [
        {
            "name": "Isaac Gantwerk Mayer (translation)",
            "bio": "From a family of musicians, Isaac Gantwerk Mayer believes that creative art is one of the most powerful ways to get in touch with the divine. He composes music and poetry in Hebrew and English.  (He also <a href=\"/index.php?user_ID=2240\">authors</a> his own original works and <a href=\"/index.php?user_ID=820\">transcribes</a> Hebrew and Aramaic text, adding niqqud and t'amim as needed.) Isaac runs a Jewish music transcription service, which will transcribe and set any Jewish music in any language, recorded or written. Contact his service on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pg/isaacgmayerjewishtranscription/\">Facebook</a> or via <a href=\"https://igmjewishcreativeworks.com/contact\">his music blog</a>.",
            "website": "https://igmjewishcreativeworks.com",
            "avatar": "https://opensiddur.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/isaac-gantwerk-mayer-2021-e1674561264977-96x96.jpg",
            "profile_link": "https://opensiddur.org/profile/isaac-gantwerk-mayer-translation"
        },
        {
            "name": "Unknown",
            "bio": "Sometimes the best we can do in attributing a historical work is to indicate the period and place it was written, the first prayer book it may have been printed in, or the archival collection in which the manuscript was found. We invite the public to help to attribute all works to their original composers. If you know something not mentioned in the commentary offered, please leave a comment or <a href=\"/contact/\">contact us</a>.",
            "website": "",
            "avatar": "https://opensiddur.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Keith-Evans-Green-Tree-Yellow-Field-CC-BY-SA-250x250.jpg",
            "profile_link": "https://opensiddur.org/profile/unknown"
        }
    ],
    "date": "2026-03-15",
    "last_updated": "2026-04-03",
    "excerpt": "A schedule for hafṯaroṯ for the weekly portions and festivals, as well as psalms for the weekly portions, according to a Damascus Karaite siddur from approximately 1700. According to the work of Jacob Mann's <em>The Bible as Read and Preached in the Old Synagogue</em> (1940), the Ḳaraite hafṭaroṯ schedule was probably adapted from the practice of the Byzantine Romaniotes, whose practice was in many ways much closer to the one attested here than to rabbinic norms practiced today. Both ultimately derive from the old Western Rite hafṭaroṯ, albeit adapted to the annual cycle originating from the east.",
    "content": "<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">\nA schedule for hafṯaroṯ for the weekly portions and festivals, as well as psalms for the weekly portions, according to a Damascus Karaite siddur from approximately 1700. According to the work of Jacob Mann&#8217;s <em>The Bible as Read and Preached in the Old Synagogue</em> (1940), the Ḳaraite hafṭaroṯ schedule was probably adapted from the practice of the Byzantine Romaniotes, whose practice was in many ways much closer to the one attested here than to rabbinic norms practiced today. Both ultimately derive from the old Western Rite hafṭaroṯ, albeit adapted to the annual cycle originating from the east.\n</div>\n<hr />\n<table style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" id=\"sortable_example\" class=\"draggable sortable\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th id=\"x\"><em>Shabbat/Festival Reading</em></th>\n<th>Haftarah portion</th>\n<th>Psalm</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\">\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Bə-reshiṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 42:1–16</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">008</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Toləḏoṯ Noaḥ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 54:1–55:5</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">029</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Lekh Ləkha</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 40:25–41:17</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">015</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yera Elav</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">II Kings 4:1–37</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">011</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ḥayye Sara</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 1:1–31</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">052</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Toləḏoṯ Yiṣḥaq</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Malachi 1:1–3:4</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">023</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yeṣe Yaȝaqoḇ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Hosea 11:7–12:14</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">132</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yishlaḥ Yaȝaqoḇ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Obadiah in its entirety</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">060</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yesheḇ Yaȝaqoḇ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Jeremiah 30:18–31:13</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">091</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yhi Mi-qeṣ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 3:15–4:1&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_1');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_1');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_1\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[1]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_1\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Note that Karaites do not celebrate Ḥanukkah, so this hafṭara is much more commonly recited than in rabbinic practice.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_1').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_1', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">039</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yigash Elav</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 37:16–28</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">133</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yəḥi Yaȝaqoḇ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 2:1–12</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">067</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Eleh Shəmoṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 16:1–14, 63</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">094</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Era el Aḇraham</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 28:24–29:21</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">076</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Bo el Parȝo</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 19:1–25</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">114</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yhi Bə-shallaḥ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Judges 4:23–5:31</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">066</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yishmaȝ Yiṯro</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 5:30–9:6</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">096</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Mishpaṭim</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Jeremiah 34:10–35:19</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">082</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ṯəruma</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 5:26–6:13</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">084</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Ata Təṣave</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 43:10–27</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">132</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ki Ṯissa</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 18:1–39</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">130</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yaqhel</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 7:13–22</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">087</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Ele Fəquḏei</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 7:40–50</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">132</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yiqra</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 43:21–44:6</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">050</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yaqhel II (leap years)<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_2');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_2');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_2\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[2]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_2\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> According to the practice of this Karaite community, during leap years these three portions are divided in half and recited over six weeks instead of three. Meanwhile,  several other readings (marked below) which are, in Rabbinic practice, divided during leap years, are never recited separately.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_2').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_2', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 56:1–58:14</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">087</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Ele Fəquḏei II (leap years)</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 7:51–8:15</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">132</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Yiqra II (leap years)</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 33:2–22</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">050</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ṣav eṯ Aharon</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Jeremiah 7:21–28, 9:22–23</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">020</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ba-Yom Ha-Shəmini</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">II Samuel 6:1–7:3</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">067</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ki Tazriaȝ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">II Kings 4:42–5:19</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">139</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Məṣoraȝ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">II Kings 7:1–20, 13:23&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_3');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_3');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_3\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[3]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_3\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> The custom of reading 7:1–20 and concluding with 13:23 is attested elsewhere, for instance in Yemenite and Italian rabbinic communities.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_3').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_3', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">039</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Aḥarei Moṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 22:1–16</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">032</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Qəḏoshim</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 20:1–6</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">016</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Emor<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_4');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_4');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_4\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[4]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_4\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Written as Amor, a common scribal mix-up of ḥataf pataḥ and ḥataf segol.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_4').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_4', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 44:15–31</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">132</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Bə-har/Im Bə-ḥuqoṯai<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_5');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_5');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_5\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[5]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_5\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Included together. It seems that in practice of this Karaite community the two were never recited separately.  See note 2.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_5').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_5', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 34:1–27</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">067</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Bə-miḏbar</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Hosea 2:1–22</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">080</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Nasso eṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Judges 13:2–24</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">067</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Bə-haȝaloṯ-kha</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Zechariah 2:14–4:9</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">037</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shəlaḥ Ləkha</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Joshua 2:1–24</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">095</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-yiqaḥ Qoraḥ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Samuel 11:14–12:22</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">055</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ḥuqqaṯ ha-Tora</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Judges 11:1–40</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">051</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-yar Balaq</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Micah 5:6–6:8</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">083</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Pinḥas<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_6');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_6');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_6\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[6]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_6\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Maṭot is not included. Perhaps in the practice of this Karaite community it was combined with Pinḥas. See note 2. In rabbinic practice, it is almost always combined with Masȝei.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_6').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_6', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Kings 18:46–19:21&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_7');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_7');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_7\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[7]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_7\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> This manuscript appears to treat each one of the twenty-two eight-verse stanzas in the great acrostic of Psalm 119 as a distinct “sub-psalm” which can be recited on its own.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_7').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_7', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">119:121–128</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Masȝei</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 40:1–41:17</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">077</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ele Ha-Dəḇarim</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Jeremiah 30:4–31:13</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">019</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Va-Eṯḥanan</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Jeremiah 32:16–39</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">017</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Haya Ȝeqeḇ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 49:14–50:10</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">119:105–112&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_8');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_8');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_8\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[8]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_8\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> See prior note.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_8').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_8', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Rə’eh Anokhi</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 54:11–55:5</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">024</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shofṭim v-Shoṭrim</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 51:12–52:10</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">058</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ki Ṯeṣe</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 54:1–17</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">144</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Haya Ki Ṯaḇo</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Hosea 14:2–10, Micah 7:18–20</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">067</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Atem Niṣaḇim<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_9');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_9');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_9\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[9]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_9\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Va-yelekh is not included. Perhaps in the practice of this Karaite community it was always combined. See note 2.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_9').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_9', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 61:10–63:1</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">040</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ha’azinu</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">II Samuel 22:1–51</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">027</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">V-Zoṯ ha-Bərakha</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Joshua 1:1–9,&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_10');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_10');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_10\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[10]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_10\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Or possibly Joshua 1:1–10 and 6:27. The instructions are ambiguous. Joshua 1:1–9 and 6:27 is attested in Yemenite practice, while most modern Karaites recite 1:1–10 without the additional verse&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_10').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_10', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> 6:27</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">067</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Yom Təruȝa<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_11');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_11');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_11\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[11]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_11\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Karaites do not refer to this day as Rosh haShanah. For more information, find <a href=\"https://www.thetorah.com/article/a-shofar-less-rosh-hashanah-a-karaites-experience-of-yom-teruah\">this article at theTorah.com</a> by the Karaite author Shawn Joe Lichaa.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_11').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_11', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Samuel 1:1–3:20</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Yom Ha-Kippurim</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Jonah in its entirety, Micah 7:18–20</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Day 1 of Ḥaḡ ha-Sukkoṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Zechariah 13:9–14:21</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shabbaṯ Purim<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_12');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_12');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_12\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[12]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_12\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> This may refer to the day rabbinic Jews refer to as Shabbaṯ Zakhor, the Shabbat before Purim. However, unlike rabbinic Jews, Karaites celebrate Purim as two days everywhere they live rather than just in certain cities. Also, the Karaite calendar is based on seeing the new moon rather than the rabbinic calendar algorithm, so the first day of Purim may also fall on Shabbat. So perhaps what is intended is any year when either day of Purim falls on Shabbaṯ. In rabbinic practice in walled cities, the hafṭara for Shabbaṯ Zakhor is repeated when Shushan Purim falls on Shabbaṯ.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_12').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_12', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">I Samuel 15:1–16:13&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_13');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_13');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_13\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[13]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_13\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Probably, based on parallel customs. Unfortunately, the manuscript only specifies it begins with a verse in I Samuel 15 that starts with &#8220;and Samuel said,&#8221; which also applies to verses 14, 16, and 17. &nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_13').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_13', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Day 1 of Ḥaḡ ha-Maṣṣoṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Joshua 3:5–7, 5:2-6:1, 6:27&#8203;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_14');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_14');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_14\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[14]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_14\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> As attested elsewhere, for instance in many Ashkenazi customs. The manuscript only  specifies 3:5 and 6:27, though, and several of its haftarot for festivals are much longer than rabbinic practice, so it is a distinct possibility that the entirety of Joshua 3:5–6:27 was intended.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_14').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_14', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shabbaṯ Pesaḥ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 36:37–37:14</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shəḇiȝi Ȝaṣeret<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_15');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_15');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_15\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[15]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_15\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Literally, the seventh day of assembly. Referring to the last day of Pesaḥ, based on Deuteronomy 16:8. Ironically, in rabbinic practice Pesaḥ is the only one of the three pilgrimage-festivals for  which “day of assembly” is not used!&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_15').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_15', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script></td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">II Samuel 22:1–51</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ḥaḡ ha-Shaḇuȝoṯ</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Ezekiel 1:1–3:12</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shabbaṯ and Rosh Ḥoḏesh</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 66:1–23</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Shabbaṯ and wedding</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\">Isaiah 61:10–63:1</td>\n<td style=\"border: 1px solid black; width:auto;\"></td>\n</tr>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<div class=\"speaker-mute footnotes_reference_container\"> <div class=\"footnote_container_prepare\"><p><span role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_reference_container_label pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container__1();\">Notes</span><span role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_reference_container_collapse_button\" style=\"display: none;; display: none;\" onclick=\"footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container__1();\"></span></p></div> <div id=\"footnote_references_container__1\" style=\"\"><table class=\"footnotes_table footnote-reference-container\"><caption class=\"accessibility\">Notes</caption> <tbody> \r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_1\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_1');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >1</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Note that Karaites do not celebrate Ḥanukkah, so this hafṭara is much more commonly recited than in rabbinic practice.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_2\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_2');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >2</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">According to the practice of this Karaite community, during leap years these three portions are divided in half and recited over six weeks instead of three. Meanwhile,  several other readings (marked below) which are, in Rabbinic practice, divided during leap years, are never recited separately.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_3\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_3');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >3</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">The custom of reading 7:1–20 and concluding with 13:23 is attested elsewhere, for instance in Yemenite and Italian rabbinic communities.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_4\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_4');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >4</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Written as Amor, a common scribal mix-up of ḥataf pataḥ and ḥataf segol.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_5\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_5');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >5</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Included together. It seems that in practice of this Karaite community the two were never recited separately.  See note 2.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_6\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_6');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >6</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Maṭot is not included. Perhaps in the practice of this Karaite community it was combined with Pinḥas. See note 2. In rabbinic practice, it is almost always combined with Masȝei.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_7\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_7');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >7</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">This manuscript appears to treat each one of the twenty-two eight-verse stanzas in the great acrostic of Psalm 119 as a distinct “sub-psalm” which can be recited on its own.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_8\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_8');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >8</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">See prior note.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_9\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_9');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >9</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Va-yelekh is not included. Perhaps in the practice of this Karaite community it was always combined. See note 2.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_10\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_10');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >10</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Or possibly Joshua 1:1–10 and 6:27. The instructions are ambiguous. Joshua 1:1–9 and 6:27 is attested in Yemenite practice, while most modern Karaites recite 1:1–10 without the additional verse</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_11\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_11');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >11</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Karaites do not refer to this day as Rosh haShanah. For more information, find <a href=\"https://www.thetorah.com/article/a-shofar-less-rosh-hashanah-a-karaites-experience-of-yom-teruah\">this article at theTorah.com</a> by the Karaite author Shawn Joe Lichaa.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_12\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_12');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >12</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">This may refer to the day rabbinic Jews refer to as Shabbaṯ Zakhor, the Shabbat before Purim. However, unlike rabbinic Jews, Karaites celebrate Purim as two days everywhere they live rather than just in certain cities. Also, the Karaite calendar is based on seeing the new moon rather than the rabbinic calendar algorithm, so the first day of Purim may also fall on Shabbat. So perhaps what is intended is any year when either day of Purim falls on Shabbaṯ. In rabbinic practice in walled cities, the hafṭara for Shabbaṯ Zakhor is repeated when Shushan Purim falls on Shabbaṯ.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_13\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_13');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >13</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Probably, based on parallel customs. Unfortunately, the manuscript only specifies it begins with a verse in I Samuel 15 that starts with &#8220;and Samuel said,&#8221; which also applies to verses 14, 16, and 17. </td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_14\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_14');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >14</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">As attested elsewhere, for instance in many Ashkenazi customs. The manuscript only  specifies 3:5 and 6:27, though, and several of its haftarot for festivals are much longer than rabbinic practice, so it is a distinct possibility that the entirety of Joshua 3:5–6:27 was intended.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_15\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_15');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >15</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Literally, the seventh day of assembly. Referring to the last day of Pesaḥ, based on Deuteronomy 16:8. Ironically, in rabbinic practice Pesaḥ is the only one of the three pilgrimage-festivals for  which “day of assembly” is not used!</td></tr>\r\n\r\n </tbody> </table> </div></div><script type=\"text/javascript\"> function footnote_expand_reference_container__1() { jQuery('#footnote_references_container__1').show(); jQuery('#footnote_reference_container_collapse_button__1').text('−'); } function footnote_collapse_reference_container__1() { jQuery('#footnote_references_container__1').hide(); jQuery('#footnote_reference_container_collapse_button__1').text('+'); } function footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container__1() { if (jQuery('#footnote_references_container__1').is(':hidden')) { footnote_expand_reference_container__1(); } else { footnote_collapse_reference_container__1(); } } function footnote_moveToReference__1(p_str_TargetID) { footnote_expand_reference_container__1(); var l_obj_Target = jQuery('#' + p_str_TargetID); if (l_obj_Target.length) { jQuery( 'html, body' ).delay( 0 ); jQuery('html, body').animate({ scrollTop: l_obj_Target.offset().top - window.innerHeight * 0.2 }, 380); } } function footnote_moveToAnchor__1(p_str_TargetID) { footnote_expand_reference_container__1(); var l_obj_Target = jQuery('#' + p_str_TargetID); if (l_obj_Target.length) { jQuery( 'html, body' ).delay( 0 ); jQuery('html, body').animate({ scrollTop: l_obj_Target.offset().top - window.innerHeight * 0.2 }, 380); } }</script>",
